        ],
        [
          "Topic Modelling",
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "5121 students",
          "1 Python Course",
          "Survey",
          "None Specified",
          "Survey Answers",
          "Question 2 of the survey is an open question where students are requested to outline their approach towards solvinfg a specific problem. \n\nThis was of course treated using a set of NLP techniques: POS tagging and Key Phrase extraction.  using KeyBERT.\n\nFor Topic Modelling Approaches, the authors explore 3 main approaches: \n\nA transformer-based approach that uses DBSCAN as clustering algorithm, while other 2 more traditional approaches (LDA and GSDMM) use a BoW representation \n\n\n\n",
          "LDDA-BoW, GSDMM-BoW, DBSCAN, OPTICS, HAC, HAC",
          "ROUGE",
          "18",
          "Strategy 1 (n=899): Write code in paper, \n\nStrategy 2 (n=307): Use information from video to answer\n\nStrategy 3 (n=106): Use IDE to correct wrong question\n\nStrategy 4 (n=51): Trial and Error\n\nStrategy 5 (n=49): Python tutor\n\nStrategy 6 (n=46): Auxiliary print statements\n\nStrategy 7 (n=35): Read instructions\n\nStrategy 8 (n=26): Use IDE shell\n\nStrategy 9 (n=18): Graceful solution from stackoverflow\n\nStrategy 10 (n=17): Pseudocode\n\nStrategy 11 (n=16): Base knowledge plus trial and error\n\nStrategy 12 (n=15): Check lecture\n\nStrategy 13 (n=14): Try on IDE\n\nStrategy 14 (n=13): Use previous knowledge\n\nStrategy 15 (n=12): Ask a friend\n\nStrategy 16 (n=9): Calm and methodic\n\nStrategy 17 (n=6): Check online resources\n\nStrategy 18 (n=5): Check and IDE and compare against expected solution  ",
          "Authors created a task-structure framework and based on their results, the selection of strategy depends on the task at hand. \n\nE.g. Coding & Debugging require different skills than Understanding the Problem. \n\nMore practical tasks usually required a more “active learning” skillset. \n\nAlso, results should be toaken with grain of salt due to the MOOC exclusive approach.",
          "Authors use a NLP pipeline to uncover different strategies to problem students from students attending a MOOC about Python programming. \n\nDifferent Topic Modelling algorithms are comapred.",
          "MOOC-based approach only\n\nConsiders only one specific set of problems (programming) in the context of one course.\n\nDoes not examine profficiency vs choice of problem-solving strategies."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
